            "question": {
                "text": "Consider the following ANSI C program: \n\nint main() { \n\n   Integer x;  \n\nreturn ();  \n\n} \n\nWhich one of the following phases in a seven-phase \nC complier will throw an error?",
                "images": [],
                "latex": [],
                "tables": []
            },
            "options": [
                {
                    "id": "A",
                    "text": "Lexical analyzer",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "B",
                    "text": "Syntax analyzer",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "C",
                    "text": "Semantic analyzer",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "D",
                    "text": "Machine dependent optimizer",
                    "images": [],
                    "latex": [],
                    "tables": []
                }
            ],
            "correctAnswer": [
                "C"
            ],
            "solution": {
                "text": "int main() {           \n       Integer x;  \n\nreturn ();  \n\n\n} \n\nTotal 13 tokens \n\nThere is no lexical error.  \n\nIn syntax analysis, the Integer x; is valid, and this \nwill be checked in semantic analysis that whether \nInteger  is a keyword or not. So, there is no syntax \nerror.  \n\nIn semantic analysis,  \n\n\n\nHere, x has no type definition.  typedef  int Integer; \nis missing before Integer x; in given ANSI C \nprogram. \nTherfore, \nthe \ngiven \nprogram \nis \nsemantically incorrect.  \n\nHence, option C is correct.",
                "images": [],
                "latex": [],
                "tables": []
            }
        },
